.TH _PRINTF 3 "March 2026" "1.0" "_printf manual"

.SH NAME
_printf \- produces output according to a format

.SH SYNOPSIS
#include "main.h"

int _printf(const char *format, ...);

.SH DESCRIPTION
The _printf function produces output according to a format string.

The format string is composed of zero or more directives. Each directive
begins with the '%' character and is followed by a conversion specifier.

The _printf function writes output to stdout.

The following conversion specifiers are supported:

.TP
.B %c
Prints a single character.

.TP
.B %s
Prints a string. If the argument is NULL, the string "(null)" is printed.

.TP
.B %%
Prints a percent sign.

.TP
.B %d
Prints a signed decimal integer.

.TP
.B %i
Prints a signed decimal integer.

If a '%' is followed by an unknown specifier, the '%' character is printed
followed by the unknown specifier.

If a '%' appears at the end of the format string, the function returns -1.

.SH RETURN VALUE
Upon successful return, _printf returns the number of characters printed
(excluding the null byte used to end output to strings).

If an error occurs, the function returns -1.

.SH EXAMPLES
_printf("Hello %s\\n", "world");

_printf("Character: %c\\n", 'A');

_printf("Percent: %%\\n");

_printf("Number: %d\\n", 1234);

.SH NOTES
This implementation does not handle:
- flag characters
- field width
- precision
- length modifiers

Output is written directly using write(2), without buffering.

.SH SEE ALSO
printf(3)

